[[File:下関豊前田商店街_先帝祭_上臈道中_壱.jpg|thumb| The Late Emperor's Festival: Procession of Ladies (Shimonoseki Toyomaeda Sho11ing Arcade)]] [[File:下関豊前田商店街_先帝祭_上臈道中_五.jpg|thumb| The Late Emperor's Festival: Procession of Ladies (Shimonoseki Toyomaeda Sho11ing Arcade)]] {{User:Immanuelle/Japanese Imperial Rituals updated}} '''Senteisai''' (先帝祭) is a festival commemorating the previous emperor.
== Classifications == Examples include: # {{ill|Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace|ja|宮中祭祀|12=draft|12=draft}} honoring the previous {{ill|Emperor of Japan|ja|天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. These major festivals are held annually on the day of the late emperor's passing. # A festival held at {{ill|Akama Shrine|ja|赤間神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shimonoseki, Yamaguchi|ja|下関市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Yamaguchi Prefecture, from May 2 to May 4. In this case, the "previous emperor" specifically refers to {{ill|Emperor Antoku|ja|安徳天皇|1=Emperor Antoku|2=ja|3=安徳天皇|4=de|5=Antoku|12=draft|12=draft}}.
=== Imperial Court Rites === As one of the major rites defined by the {{ill|Imperial Household Rites Ordinance|ja|皇室祭祀令|12=draft|12=draft}}, it is held annually on the day of the previous emperor's passing. The actual name of the ritual replaces "Senteisai" with the posthumous title of the emperor.
Although the Imperial Household Rites Ordinance was abolished in 1947, the tradition continues as an Imperial Court rite. During the {{ill|Heisei period|ja|平成|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Emperor Shōwa Festival|ja|昭和天皇祭|12=draft|12=draft}} was conducted, and following the abdication of Emperor Akihito on April 30, 2019, the Emperor Shōwa Festival continues as the most recent commemoration of a deceased emperor into the {{ill|Reiwa period|ja|令和|12=draft|12=draft}}.
On the day of Senteisai, it was previously designated a public holiday under the former laws "Holiday Law" and "Regulations on Holidays." However, it was removed from the list of holidays with the enactment of the current "Act on National Holidays" in 1948.
{| class="wikitable" |+ Senteisai after the Meiji period |- ! Era !! Senteisai !! Date |- | {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft}} || {{ill|Emperor Kōmei|ja|孝明天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} Festival || January 30 |- | {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|12=draft|12=draft}} || {{ill|Emperor Meiji|ja|明治天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} Festival || July 30 |- | {{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft|12=draft}} || {{ill|Emperor Taishō|ja|大正天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} Festival || December 25 |- | {{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|12=draft|12=draft}} || Emperor Shōwa Festival || January 7 |- | {{ill|Reiwa|ja|令和|12=draft|12=draft}} || Emperor Shōwa Festival || January 7 |}
=== Akama Shrine (Shimonoseki, Yamaguchi Prefecture) Festival === Following the {{ill|Battle of Dan-no-ura|ja|壇ノ浦の戦い|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1186 (Bunji 2), {{ill|Emperor Go-Toba|ja|後鳥羽天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} issued a decree to Nagato Province for the enshrinement of Emperor Antoku's remains at Amidaji Temple (now Akama Shrine). A commemorative festival called the "Senteikai" was held annually on his death anniversary (March 24), which later became the "Main Festival" on April 23 under the Gregorian calendar and was eventually moved to the current date of May 2.
On May 2, ceremonies such as the "Goryōmae Festival," attended by the {{ill|National Heike Association|ja|全国平家会|12=draft|12=draft}}, are held. On May 3, the "Nakajima Group's Pilgrimage Ceremony" follows, inspired by a story of loyalists visiting the shrine. This is succeeded by the "U11er-class Women's Procession" (Jōrō Dōchū), a tradition rooted in the courtesans and later geisha who honored Emperor Antoku. The procession features participants dressed in court attire, ste11ing in the traditional {{ill|Soto Hachimonji|ja|外八文字|12=draft|12=draft}} style through Shimonoseki.
The main festival concludes on May 4 with the {{ill|Shinko Festival|ja|神幸祭|12=draft|12=draft}}.
This festival, alongside the {{ill|Kokura Gion Festival|ja|小倉祇園祭|12=draft|12=draft}} across the Kanmon Straits in Kitakyushu, is known for the saying, "If it doesn't rain at Senteisai in Seki or Gion in Kokura, money will pour like rain," highlighting the lively crowds.
The festival is designated an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|無形民俗文化財|12=draft|12=draft}} of Shimonoseki City<ref>[http://www.stca-kanko.or.jp/sightseeing/city_summary/events/ Shimonoseki Tourism and Convention Association]</ref>.
