== Classifications == Examples include: # {{ill|Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace|ja|宮中祭祀|1=Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace|lt=Ceremonies of the Japanese Imperial Palace|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} honoring the previous {{ill|Emperor of Japan|ja|天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}. These major festivals are held annually on the day of the late emperor's passing. # A festival held at {{ill|Akama Shrine|ja|赤間神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shimonoseki, Yamaguchi|ja|下関市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, Yamaguchi Prefecture, from May 2 to May 4. In this case, the "previous emperor" specifically refers to {{ill|Emperor Antoku|ja|安徳天皇|1=Emperor Antoku|2=ja|3=安徳天皇|4=de|5=Antoku|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.
=== Imperial Court Rites === As one of the major rites defined by the {{ill|Imperial Household Rites Ordinance|ja|皇室祭祀令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, it is held annually on the day of the previous emperor's passing. The actual name of the ritual replaces "Senteisai" with the posthumous title of the emperor.
Although the Imperial Household Rites Ordinance was abolished in 1947, the tradition continues as an Imperial Court rite. During the {{ill|Heisei period|ja|平成|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Emperor Shōwa Festival|ja|昭和天皇祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} was conducted, and following the abdication of Emperor Akihito on April 30, 2019, the Emperor Shōwa Festival continues as the most recent commemoration of a deceased emperor into the {{ill|Reiwa period|ja|令和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.
On the day of Senteisai, it was previously designated a public holiday under the former laws "Holiday Law" and "Regulations on Holidays." However, it was removed from the list of holidays with the enactment of the current "Act on National Holidays" in 1948.
