=== Akama Shrine (Shimonoseki, Yamaguchi Prefecture) Festival === Following the {{ill|Battle of Dan-no-ura|ja|壇ノ浦の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} in 1186 (Bunji 2), {{ill|Emperor Go-Toba|ja|後鳥羽天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} issued a decree to Nagato Province for the enshrinement of Emperor Antoku's remains at Amidaji Temple (now Akama Shrine). A commemorative festival called the "Senteikai" was held annually on his death anniversary (March 24), which later became the "Main Festival" on April 23 under the Gregorian calendar and was eventually moved to the current date of May 2.
On May 2, ceremonies such as the "Goryōmae Festival," attended by the {{ill|National Heike Association|ja|全国平家会|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, are held. On May 3, the "Nakajima Group's Pilgrimage Ceremony" follows, inspired by a story of loyalists visiting the shrine. This is succeeded by the "U11er-class Women's Procession" (Jōrō Dōchū), a tradition rooted in the courtesans and later geisha who honored Emperor Antoku. The procession features participants dressed in court attire, ste11ing in the traditional {{ill|Soto Hachimonji|ja|外八文字|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} style through Shimonoseki.
The main festival concludes on May 4 with the {{ill|Shinko Festival|ja|神幸祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.
This festival, alongside the {{ill|Kokura Gion Festival|ja|小倉祇園祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} across the Kanmon Straits in Kitakyushu, is known for the saying, "If it doesn't rain at Senteisai in Seki or Gion in Kokura, money will pour like rain," highlighting the lively crowds.
The festival is designated an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} of Shimonoseki City<ref>[http://www.stca-kanko.or.jp/sightseeing/city_summary/events/ Shimonoseki Tourism and Convention Association]</ref>.
